Breaking down join() (comments added in place)
	croom = &rooms[a]; // current room
	troom = &rooms[b]; // target room
The next block picks based on the relative locations of current and target rooms. I'll just pull apart the first if:
	if(troom->lx > croom->hx) { // target room is fully to the right of current room
		dx = 1; // corridor traveling to the right
		dy = 0; // non vertical
		xx = croom->hx+1; // column on the right wall of current room
		tx = troom->lx-1; // column on the left wall of target room
		finddpos(&cc, xx, croom->ly, xx, croom->hy); // find a position 'cc' in the right wall of current room
		finddpos(&tt, tx, troom->ly, tx, troom->hy); // find a position 'tt' in the left wall of target room
	}
Then we set variables
	xx = cc.x; // door position on current room
	yy = cc.y;
	tx = tt.x - dx; // square directly in front of wall on target room
	ty = tt.y - dy;
And we get our first instance of nxcor!
	if(nxcor && levl[xx+dx][yy+dy].typ) // if the square directly in front of the wall in our current room is anything but stone
		return; // end early, join() did nothing
I'll skip the shared-wall-door-making, as that's not vanilla.
Our second use of nxcor...
	// on wall of current room
	if (okdoor(xx,yy) || !nxcor) // if it's an ok place for a door, or !nxcor
	    dodoor(xx,yy,croom); // make the door here
Dig a corridor, return early if it fails... nxcor here allows the corridor to fail 'for no reason' partway through.
	org.x  = xx+dx; org.y  = yy+dy;
	dest.x = tx; dest.y = ty;

	if (!dig_corridor(&org, &dest, nxcor,
			level.flags.arboreal ? ROOM : CORR, STONE))
	    return;
And our final use of nxcor:
	// on wall of target room
	if (okdoor(tt.x, tt.y) || !nxcor) // if it's an ok place for a door, or !nxcor
	    dodoor(tt.x, tt.y, troom); // make the door here
Huh.
Now where can these target locations be? [xx,yy] was determined earlier by finddpos():
finddpos(cc, xl,yl,xh,yh)
coord *cc;
xchar xl,yl,xh,yh;
{
	register xchar x, y;

	x = (xl == xh) ? xl : (xl + rn2(xh-xl+1));
	y = (yl == yh) ? yl : (yl + rn2(yh-yl+1));
	if(okdoor(x, y))
		goto gotit;

	for(x = xl; x <= xh; x++) for(y = yl; y <= yh; y++)
		if(okdoor(x, y))
			goto gotit;

	for(x = xl; x <= xh; x++) for(y = yl; y <= yh; y++)
		if(IS_DOOR(levl[x][y].typ) || levl[x][y].typ == SDOOR)
			goto gotit;
	/* cannot find something reasonable -- strange */
	x = xl;
	y = yh;
gotit:
	cc->x = x;
	cc->y = y;
	return;
}
Which can ONLY get coordinates of okdoor() or DOOR or SDOOR (or the bottom left corner, which we don't see happening).
Therefore, all that the !nxcor is doing is allowing us to add doors on top of doors. Which is dumb. Vanilla doesn't run into the maxdoors issue because I amped up roomcount in dnh levelgen, so it makes many more attempts to join() rooms and can create doors on top of doors like this enough times to reach MAXDOOR.
